## 2. Integration Scenarios

### SC-001 — <!-- User registration happy path -->

**Category**: integration

**Description**: <!-- Verify the full registration flow from API request through service processing to database persistence, confirming the Arch sequence diagram is realised at runtime. -->

**Source**: <!-- ARCH-DIAG-001 (registration sequence) -->

**Preconditions**

- <!-- All services healthy -->
- <!-- Database migrated and empty -->

**Steps**

| # | Action | Type | Details |
|---|--------|------|---------|
| 1 | <!-- POST /api/v1/users --> | <!-- http_request --> | <!-- payload: {"email": "test@example.com", "name": "Test User"} --> |
| 2 | <!-- Query users table --> | <!-- db_query --> | <!-- SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = 'test@example.com' --> |

**Expected Results**

| Type | Condition |
|------|-----------|
| response | <!-- HTTP 201, body contains user id --> |
| metric | <!-- http_requests_total{status="201", method="POST", path="/api/v1/users"} incremented by 1 --> |
| log | <!-- Structured log entry with event="user_created", user_id=<id> --> |

**Evidence to Collect**: <!-- response body, PromQL query result, LogQL query result -->

**Arch Refs**: <!-- ARCH-DIAG-001 -->
**RE Refs**: <!-- FR-001 (user registration acceptance criteria) -->

## 3. Failure Scenarios

### SC-101 — <!-- Database unavailability handling -->

**Category**: failure

**Description**: <!-- Verify graceful degradation when PostgreSQL becomes unavailable, confirming circuit breaker / fallback behaviour from IMPL-IDR-001. -->

**Source**: <!-- ARCH-COMP-001 dependencies → postgres -->

**Preconditions**

- <!-- All services healthy and warmed up with at least one successful request -->

**Steps**

| # | Action | Type | Details |
|---|--------|------|---------|
| 1 | <!-- docker stop postgres --> | <!-- fault_injection --> | <!-- Simulate database outage --> |
| 2 | <!-- POST /api/v1/users --> | <!-- http_request --> | <!-- Expect graceful error response --> |
| 3 | <!-- Wait 10s, check metrics --> | <!-- metric_query --> | <!-- PromQL: rate(http_requests_total{status=~"5.."}[1m]) --> |
| 4 | <!-- docker start postgres --> | <!-- recovery --> | <!-- Restore database --> |
| 5 | <!-- POST /api/v1/users --> | <!-- http_request --> | <!-- Expect successful response after recovery --> |

**Expected Results**

| Type | Condition |
|------|-----------|
| response | <!-- HTTP 503 during outage, HTTP 201 after recovery --> |
| metric | <!-- Error rate spike visible in Prometheus --> |
| log | <!-- Error-level log with database connection failure details --> |

**Evidence to Collect**: <!-- HTTP responses, PromQL error rate query, LogQL error search -->

**Arch Refs**: <!-- ARCH-COMP-001 -->
**SLO Refs**: <!-- SLO-001 (availability) -->

## 4. Load Scenarios

### SC-201 — <!-- Baseline throughput check -->

**Category**: load

**Description**: <!-- Light smoke-level load test to confirm the system handles concurrent requests without errors under minimal load. Not a performance benchmark. -->

**Steps**

| # | Action | Type | Details |
|---|--------|------|---------|
| 1 | <!-- Send 10 concurrent requests --> | <!-- load_injection --> | <!-- 10 parallel POST /api/v1/users with unique emails --> |
| 2 | <!-- Collect response times --> | <!-- metric_query --> | <!-- PromQL: histogram_quantile(0.99, http_request_duration_seconds_bucket) --> |

**Expected Results**

| Type | Condition |
|------|-----------|
| response | <!-- All 10 requests return 201 --> |
| metric | <!-- p99 latency < SLO threshold --> |

